<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:.5in;mso-pagination:none;mso-layo=
ut-grid-align:
none;text-autospace:none'><b style=3D'mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>&quot;Du=
e to
its marginal existence in relation to the oppressive reality of work, play =
is
often regarded as fictitious. But the work of the <span class=3DSpellE>situ=
ationists</span>
is precisely the preparation of <span class=3DSpellE>ludic</span> possibili=
ties
to come.&quot; </b>(Guy <span class=3DSpellE>Debord</span>, Contribution to=
 <span
class=3DSpellE>Situationist</span> Definition of Play, <span class=3DSpellE=
>Internationale</span>
<span class=3DSpellE>Situationniste</span> #1, June 1958) </p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'mso-pagination:none;mso-layout-grid-align:non=
e;
text-autospace:none'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'line-height:26.0pt;mso-pagination:none;mso-la=
yout-grid-align:
none;text-autospace:none'>In recent years, commentators on game culture and=
 <span
class=3DSpellE>ludology</span> have undertaken the task of analyzing and
structuring play.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>Such work h=
as
been strongly influenced by the Dutch researcher Johan Huizinga's 1938 stud=
y of
play, Homo <span class=3DSpellE>Ludens</span> and Roger <span class=3DSpell=
E>Callois's</span>
later <span class=3DSpellE>structuralist</span> elaborations of Huizinga&#8=
217;s
research.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>In this article I w=
ant to
draw upon a different stream of thought from the mid twentieth century, also
informed by Huizinga but not exclusively<span class=3DGramE>,<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>that</span> of the Paris <span
class=3DSpellE>Situationist</span> artists and architects, including Guy <s=
pan
class=3DSpellE>Debord</span> and Gilles <span class=3DSpellE>Ivian</span> (=
also
known as <span style=3D'font-size:10.0pt'>[Ivan <span class=3DSpellE>Chtche=
glov</span>)</span>.
A number of important <span class=3DGramE>engagements</span> with play and =
games
by the <span class=3DSpellE>Situationists</span> are newly relevant today.<=
span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>Rather than offer a historical
assessment of <span class=3DSpellE>Situationism&#8217;s</span> theories, I =
will
take cues from their writings to reconsider the potential of games in art.<=
span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>I find useful their critique of pl=
ay
within but nevertheless resistant to capitalism (and by extension imperiali=
sm
and militarism), their architectural proposals for &quot;player&quot;
navigation and transformation of urban &quot;<span class=3DSpellE>psychogeo=
graphic</span>&quot;
zones (what we might call &#8220;<span class=3DSpellE>ludic</span>
architecture&#8221;), their analysis of leisure and non-leisure activities,=
 and
their repurposing of Dadaist negativity. These proposals all have direct
relevance to what <span class=3DSpellE>MacKenzie</span> <span class=3DSpell=
E>Wark</span>
calls our contemporary condition of &quot;<span class=3DSpellE>Gamespace</s=
pan>.&#8221;
(<span class=3DSpellE>MacKenzie</span> <span class=3DSpellE>Wark</span>, Ga=
mer
Theory, Harvard University Press, 2007)</p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'line-height:26.0pt;mso-pagination:none;mso-la=
yout-grid-align:
none;text-autospace:none'><span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'line-height:26.0pt;mso-pagination:none;mso-la=
yout-grid-align:
none;text-autospace:none'>Lesson 1: Freeing play</p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'line-height:26.0pt;mso-pagination:none;mso-la=
yout-grid-align:
none;text-autospace:none'><span style=3D'mso-tab-count:1'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp=
;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>A
promising tactic for the early <span class=3DSpellE>Situationists</span> wa=
s the
unpredictable yet forceful potential of play &#8212; what anthropologist Vi=
ctor
Turner termed the &#8220;<span class=3DSpellE>liminoid</span>,&#8221; or the
freeing and transformational, moments of play when the normal roles and rul=
es
of a community or society are relaxed. (<span class=3DGramE>via</span> Jon =
<span
class=3DSpellE>Dovey</span> and Helen W. Kennedy, Game Cultures, Open Unive=
rsity
Press, 2006) After these temporary (TAZ like) situations &quot;players&quot;
settle once more <span class=3DGramE>into<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&=
nbsp;
</span>fixed</span> roles.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>Th=
e <span
class=3DSpellE>Situationists</span> proposed<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>to adopt this <span class=3D=
SpellE>liminoid</span>
&quot;subjunctive mood&quot;, when anything can happen, the carnival, Anarc=
hy
Online the RPG, the Society of Creative Anachronisms, into a more general
approach, a way of doing and being in the everyday, in order to transform
material life with <span class=3DSpellE>ludic</span> actions.</p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'line-height:26.0pt;mso-pagination:none;mso-la=
yout-grid-align:
none;text-autospace:none'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-top:5.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bott=
om:5.0pt;
margin-left:.5in;mso-pagination:none;mso-layout-grid-align:none;text-autosp=
ace:
none'><b style=3D'mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>&quot;We must develop a syst=
ematic
intervention based on the complex factors of two components in perpetual
interaction: the material environment of life and the behaviors which it gi=
ves
rise to and which radically transform it. Our action on behavior, linked wi=
th
other desirable aspects of a revolution in mores, can be briefly defined as=
 the
invention of games of an essentially new type.&quot; (Guy <span class=3DSpe=
llE>Debord</span>,
</b>Report on the Construction of Situations and on the International <span
class=3DSpellE>Situationist</span> Tendency's Conditions of Organization and
Action, <b style=3D'mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>June 1957)<o:p></o:p></b><=
/p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-top:5.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bott=
om:5.0pt;
margin-left:0in;line-height:200%;mso-pagination:none;mso-layout-grid-align:
none;text-autospace:none'><span class=3DSpellE>Situationist</span> games do=
 not
respect the boundary between play and work, leisure and non-leisure, between
&#8220;real life&#8221; <span class=3DGramE>and<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>Huizinga's</span> &quot;magic
circle&quot;, the separation from &#8220;normal space&#8221; that facilitat=
es
immersion in games and play. (Katie <span class=3DSpellE>Salen</span> and E=
ric
Zimmerman, Rules of Play)<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span><sp=
an
class=3DSpellE>Situationist</span> games are not sports and are not relegat=
ed to
sports stadiums, arcades, or <span class=3DSpellE>Playstation</span> home
entertainment set-ups.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span><span
class=3DSpellE>Situationist</span> games bleed into the city, the workplace=
, the <span
class=3DSpellE>buyplace</span>, the personal computer, the mobile phone<span
class=3DGramE>,<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>public</span>=
 and
private transportation and communication, and into and inside escapist
rule-based game environments themselves. In transgressing the &#8220;magic
circle,&#8221; a <span class=3DSpellE>Situationist</span> gaming tactic att=
empts
to give transformative potential not just to play but to &#8220;normal&#822=
1;
life.</p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'line-height:26.0pt;mso-pagination:none;mso-la=
yout-grid-align:
none;text-autospace:none'>Lesson 2: Wretched winnings, or challenging
competition</p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'mso-pagination:none;mso-layout-grid-align:non=
e;
text-autospace:none'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-top:5.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bott=
om:5.0pt;
margin-left:.5in;mso-pagination:none;mso-layout-grid-align:none;text-autosp=
ace:
none'><b style=3D'mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>&quot;The feeling of the
importance of winning in the game, that it is about concrete satisfactions
&#8212; or, more often than not, illusions &#8212; is the wretched product =
of a
wretched society.&quot;</b> (Guy <span class=3DSpellE>Debord</span>, Contri=
bution
to <span class=3DSpellE>Situationist</span> Definition of Play) </p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-top:5.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bott=
om:5.0pt;
margin-left:0in;line-height:200%;mso-pagination:none;mso-layout-grid-align:
none;text-autospace:none'>The <span class=3DSpellE>Situationists</span> were
critical of the competitive aspects of play, <span class=3DSpellE>Callois</=
span>'
&quot;<span class=3DSpellE>agon</span>&quot;.<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>For them, competition was complici=
t with
capitalism, with the British working class fan's mindless absorption in
football, with the struggle to obtain material goods, investing in lucrative
defense stocks, doing whatever it takes to be the last Survivor on the isla=
nd,
playing to get the biggest <span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;</span>fa=
mily
home in the Sims neighborhood. The <span class=3DSpellE>Situationists</span=
>,
like avid gamers, rejected the capitalist derived division between producti=
on
and consumption, active work vs. passive <span class=3DSpellE>liesure</span=
>.
Nevertheless, they did acknowledge that an element of competition might be
necessary in their games: </p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-top:5.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bott=
om:5.0pt;
margin-left:.5in;mso-pagination:none;mso-layout-grid-align:none;text-autosp=
ace:
none'><b style=3D'mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>&quot;The only success that =
can be
conceived in play is the immediate success of its ambiance, and the constant
augmentation of its powers<span class=3DGramE>..</span>[ ]..<span class=3DG=
ramE>play</span>
cannot be completely emancipated from a competitive aspect&quot;</b>(Guy <s=
pan
class=3DSpellE>Debord</span>, Contribution to <span class=3DSpellE>Situatio=
nist</span>
Definition of Play)<b style=3D'mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'> <o:p></o:p></b=
></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'line-height:26.0pt;mso-pagination:none;mso-la=
yout-grid-align:
none;text-autospace:none'>In our adaptation of <span class=3DSpellE>Situati=
onist</span>
games, perhaps we allow for a degree of competition, among other motivating
playful components.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span><span
class=3DSpellE>Morever</span>, for the <span class=3DSpellE>Situationists</=
span>, <span
class=3DSpellE>ludic</span> actions were also ethical navigations, and ther=
efore
the goal of a competition should always be questioned.<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>(Guy <span class=3DSpellE>Debord</=
span>,
Contribution to <span class=3DSpellE>Situationist</span> Definition of Play=
) </p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'line-height:26.0pt;mso-pagination:none;mso-la=
yout-grid-align:
none;text-autospace:none'>Lesson 3: Virtual game worlds: Toward a <span
class=3DSpellE>ludic</span> architecture</p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'mso-pagination:none;mso-layout-grid-align:non=
e;
text-autospace:none'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-top:5.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bott=
om:5.0pt;
margin-left:.5in;mso-pagination:none;mso-layout-grid-align:none;text-autosp=
ace:
none'><b style=3D'mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>&quot;The architecture of to=
morrow
will be a means of modifying present conceptions of time and space. It will=
 be
a means of knowledge and a means of action&quot;(</b><span style=3D'mso-bid=
i-font-size:
10.0pt'>Gilles <span class=3DSpellE>Ivain</span> [Ivan <span class=3DSpellE=
>Chtcheglov</span>],
Formulary for a New Urbanism, October 1953 printed in <span class=3DSpellE>=
Internationale</span>
<span class=3DSpellE>Situationniste</span> #1)<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-top:5.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bott=
om:5.0pt;
margin-left:.5in;mso-pagination:none;mso-layout-grid-align:none;text-autosp=
ace:
none'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'line-height:200%;mso-pagination:none;mso-layo=
ut-grid-align:
none;text-autospace:none'><span class=3DSpellE>Situationist</span> Russian
architect Gilles <span class=3DSpellE>Ivain</span><span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>imagined a <span class=3DSpellE>a<=
/span>
&quot;playful-constructive&quot; movement through a city's &quot;<span
class=3DSpellE>psychogeographic</span>&quot; zones, urban zones defined not=
 only
by streets, buildings and businesses but also by how people inhabit the city
and the collective psychic ambiances they project.<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>Or as Guy <span class=3DSpellE>Deb=
ord</span>
later wrote, while describing the now famous <span class=3DSpellE>Situation=
ist</span>
notion of <span class=3DSpellE>d&eacute;rive</span>, or drifting through a =
city: <span
class=3DGramE><b style=3D'mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>from a <span class=
=3DSpellE>d&eacute;rive</span>
point of view cities</b></span><b style=3D'mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'> ha=
ve <span
class=3DSpellE>psychogeographical</span> contours, with constant currents, =
fixed
points and vortexes that strongly discourage entry into or exit from certain
zones</b>. High speed <span class=3DSpellE>surviellance</span> cameras trac=
king
shopping patterns in stores like the Gap map these hidden currents, <span
class=3DGramE>a<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>time</span> b=
ased
techno-<span class=3DSpellE>capatilist</span> development of the study of <=
span
class=3DSpellE>psychogeographic</span> zoning the <span class=3DSpellE>Situ=
ationists</span>
did not forecast for their fledgling &quot;science.&quot;</p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'mso-pagination:none;mso-layout-grid-align:non=
e;
text-autospace:none'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:.5in;mso-pagination:none;mso-layo=
ut-grid-align:
none;text-autospace:none'><b style=3D'mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>&quot;Wi=
th the
aid of old maps, aerial photographs and experimental <span class=3DSpellE>d=
&eacute;rives</span>,
one can draw up hitherto lacking maps of influences, maps whose inevitable
imprecision at this early stage is no worse than that of the first navigati=
onal
charts. The only difference is that it is no longer a matter of precisely
delineating stable continents, but of changing architecture and
urbanism.&quot;(</b><span style=3D'mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'>Guy <span
class=3DSpellE>Debord</span><span class=3DGramE>,<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>Theory</span> of the <span class=
=3DSpellE>D&eacute;rive</span>,
Les <span class=3DSpellE>L&egrave;vres</span> <span class=3DSpellE>Nues</sp=
an> #9,
November 1956, reprinted in <span class=3DSpellE>Internationale</span> <span
class=3DSpellE>Situationniste</span> #2, December 1958)</span><b
style=3D'mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><o:p></o:p></b></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'line-height:26.0pt;mso-pagination:none;mso-la=
yout-grid-align:
none;text-autospace:none'>Beyond the remapping of existing cities as <span
class=3DSpellE>psychogeographic</span> zones, new city forms were imagined.=
 In
&quot;Formulary for a New Urbanism&quot;, from the first edition of <span
class=3DSpellE>Situationist</span>, Gilles <span class=3DSpellE><span class=
=3DGramE>Ivain</span></span><span
class=3DGramE><span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>describes</spa=
n> a
futuristic <span class=3DSpellE>situationist</span> city's quarters, and pu=
blic
and private architecture that would be in continuous flux and modifiable
according to the whims of the<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;
</span>inhabitants, including zones such as a Bizarre Quarter &#8212; a Hap=
py
Quarter (specially reserved for habitation)<span
