<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'line-height:26.0pt;mso-pagination:none;mso-la=
yout-grid-align:
none;text-autospace:none'>Lesson 6: Games inside games: Interventionist tac=
tics
in virtual spaces</p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'line-height:26.0pt;mso-pagination:none;mso-la=
yout-grid-align:
none;text-autospace:none'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'line-height:26.0pt;mso-pagination:none;mso-la=
yout-grid-align:
none;text-autospace:none'>In their handbook for game designers, <span
class=3DSpellE>Salen</span> and Zimmerman repeatedly <span class=3DGramE>em=
phasize<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>the</span> importance of the &quot=
;magic
circle&quot; and the investment of the player in a separate, pretend space =
of
play (whether abstract or photorealistic, virtual or non-digital).<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>They stress the pleasure in follow=
ing
the rules of games within the clear-cut boundaries of this magic circle. <s=
pan
class=3DSpellE>Situationist</span> gamers, however, are more akin to the cr=
eative
cheater, the game &quot;<span class=3DSpellE>griefer</span>&quot; or the
hacker.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>They blur the periphe=
ries
of the magic circle, taking pleasure in changing the rules of the existing =
<span
class=3DSpellE>gamespace</span>, which they see as problematic in a fixed s=
tate. <span
class=3DSpellE>Situationist</span> <span class=3DSpellE>mods</span> and hac=
ks
intervening inside preexisting games can be more entertaining than the orig=
inal
game.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>For instance, the popul=
ar
Massively Multiplayer Online Role Playing Game (MMORPG) Second Life has been
playfully manipulated by the avatar <span class=3DSpellE>Gazira</span> <span
class=3DSpellE>Babeli</span>, one of the members of the Second Front collec=
tive
of Second Life artistic hackers.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;
</span>Her Gray Goo hack was an infestation of Second Life space with
out-of-control repetitive self-replicating objects, inspired by <span
class=3DSpellE>nanotechnological</span> disaster scenarios. Grey Goo took v=
arious
forms, from endless Mario character replications to rampant Velvet Undergro=
und
bananas.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>It was so effective =
it
slowed down Linden Lab's game servers, interfering with game play
system-wide.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span><span class=3DSp=
ellE>Babeli&#8217;s</span>
COME.TO.HEAVEN similarly exploited a loophole in Second Life which allows
players to create gigantic avatars in proportion to the Second Life world,
resulting in unexpected interesting glitches. While the identity (identitie=
s)
behind the <span class=3DSpellE>Babeli</span> avatar are kept secret, the c=
ode
for her Second Life interventions are always made public by posting it onli=
ne
so others can learn from it and reuse it.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&=
nbsp;
</span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'line-height:26.0pt;mso-pagination:none;mso-la=
yout-grid-align:
none;text-autospace:none'>A similar, <span class=3DSpellE>Situationist</spa=
n>-themed
interventionist game strategy is offered by Pierre <span class=3DSpellE>Rah=
ola</span>,
a French gamer and DJ.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>During=
 the
early phase of the US war on Iraq, <span class=3DSpellE>Rahola</span> and h=
is
collaborators would spray anti-war graffiti inside online shooter games.<sp=
an
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>When I interviewed him in Pa=
ris in
2005, he admitted that &#8220;intervening in games is more fun than playing=
 the
game.&#8221;<span style=3D'mso-tab-count:1'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&=
nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>Around
the same time Pierre and his friends were playing online shooter games with=
 an
activist edge I began a body of work I would describe as <span class=3DSpel=
lE>situationist</span>
gaming.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>In collaboratio=
n with
the artists Brody Condon and Joan <span class=3DSpellE>Leandre</span>, we
initiated Velvet-Strike, tagging the then-popular online soldier shooter ga=
me
Counter-Strike with anti-war graffiti.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbs=
