<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'line-height:26.0pt;mso-pagination:none;mso-la=
yout-grid-align:
none;text-autospace:none'><span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;
</span>Operation Urban Terrain (OUT) was another project I initiated to war=
p an
existing <span class=3DSpellE>gamespace</span> &#8212; the free US army
propaganda game America's Army.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp;
</span>With OUT, I wanted to counter the convergence of military and civili=
an
space with a kind of activism that merged virtual urban game space wireless=
ly
with <span class=3DSpellE>cityspace</span>.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'=
>&nbsp;
</span>I invited many people whom I had met online through Velvet-Strike to
participate, including Chris <span class=3DSpellE>Birke</span>, one of the
original Counter-Strike game <span class=3DSpellE>texturers</span>, Mexico =
City
architect Luis Hernandez and Pierre <span class=3DSpellE>Rahola</span>. We
projected our live performances onto the walls and surfaces of Manhattan and
Brooklyn, connected wirelessly to five players around the world during the =
NYC
Republican National Convention of 2004.<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nb=
sp;
</span>I matched virtual locations within the America's Army game servers w=
ith
physical New York City sites, projecting a live performance of a virtual si=
t-in
inside a tunnel with yellow taxis onto a building in midtown Manhattan, whe=
re
there were many yellow taxis, and pairing a red brick warehouse in the game
with a brick building in Harlem. For the last location I <span class=3DGram=
E>merged<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>a</span> live soldier dancing
performance<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>in the popular
America's Army map &quot;Bridge&quot; with<span style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>=
&nbsp;
</span>projection onto the Manhattan Bridge in Brooklyn.</p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'line-height:26.0pt;mso-pagination:none;mso-la=
yout-grid-align:
none;text-autospace:none'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'line-height:26.0pt;mso-pagination:none;mso-la=
yout-grid-align:
none;text-autospace:none'>Riot Gear for <span class=3DSpellE>Rollartista</s=
pan>,
another game inside a game, was a series of <span class=3DSpellE>machinima<=
/span>
performances calling attention to European and British police abuse of Isla=
mic
and African immigrants, with players wearing padded &quot;riot gear&quot;
costumes designed in collaboration with artist <span class=3DSpellE>Talice<=
/span>
Lee. In the first performance of the project, two player/performers
roller-skated around the small Spanish city of Castellon projecting the
Playstation2 games <span class=3DSpellE>Narc</span> and <span class=3DSpell=
E>Mechwarrior</span>
from an ultra light projector attached to one of the player's helmets,
(technology had developed since the heavy battery and projector of OUT).<sp=
an
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>At each projection location in the=
 city,
one player &quot;roller-danced&quot; and handed out flyers<span
style=3D'mso-spacerun:yes'>&nbsp; </span>with stories of immigrant abuse to
interested passers-by while the second player performed with a portable <sp=
an
class=3DSpellE>Playstation</span>, controlling a dancing policeman characte=
r who
violently beats up on civilian city dwellers.</p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'line-height:26.0pt;mso-pagination:none;mso-la=
yout-grid-align:
none;text-autospace:none'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'line-height:26.0pt;mso-pagination:none;mso-la=
yout-grid-align:
none;text-autospace:none'>Conclusion</p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'line-height:26.0pt;mso-pagination:none;mso-la=
yout-grid-align:
none;text-autospace:none'>The <span class=3DSpellE>Situationists</span> pre=
dicted
an age of expanded <span class=3DSpellE>ludic</span> possibilities for arti=
sts
and for anyone. Paraphrasing and remixing both gamer Rebecca Cannon and <sp=
an
class=3DSpellE>Situationist</span> architect Gilles <span class=3DSpellE>Iv=
ain</span>,
we are bored with shooter games. We are bored with the suburbs, the stale
imperialist sexist engineering biased corporate game industry, and with new
academic <span class=3DSpellE>ludology</span> that reifies existing
superstructures. We are ready to play reality TV off camera. We are frustra=
ted
with our governments and the military superstructures that control <span
class=3DSpellE>gamespace</span>. We don't want to play by rules we never ag=
reed
upon in the first place. Anyways, even if we had fun playing those games to
begin with, it is now more entertaining to mess them up, or to invent new
unsanctioned games inside <span class=3DSpellE>gamespace</span>. If big pla=
yers
are intervening in <span class=3DSpellE>gamespace</span>, then it is time f=
or <span
class=3DSpellE>Situationist</span> gaming.</p>

